1
00:00:00,291 --> 00:00:02,625
Interviewer: Regarding
the three cells you were in...

2
00:00:02,666 --> 00:00:04,708
How did you spend
your time in them

3
00:00:05,166 --> 00:00:08,291
Is there a particular memory
from those cells you can’t forget?

4
00:00:09,416 --> 00:00:12,791
How did you feel when
we walked in them?

5
00:00:14,333 --> 00:00:18,875
I felt that when I entered my hand
was there, and when I left it wasn’t

6
00:00:19,291 --> 00:00:20,666
I spent the time sleeping

7
00:00:21,208 --> 00:00:23,375
Only when prayer time came, I
prayed and went back to sleep

8
00:00:25,541 --> 00:00:29,541
Interviewer: How did
the ISIS jailers treat you?

9
00:00:29,583 --> 00:00:31,416
At prayer times...

10
00:00:31,416 --> 00:00:34,791
Did they act violently to
make you stand up for prayer?

11
00:00:34,958 --> 00:00:40,833
They came at prayer time and
knocked on the door, on the bars

12
00:00:42,166 --> 00:00:44,708
Shouting—It’s prayer
time, get up, pray, get up

13
00:00:45,541 --> 00:00:47,375
Interviewer: Did they supervise your performance of the prayer?
Witness: What do you mean?

14
00:00:49,083 --> 00:00:52,708
Interviewer: Meaning they came to
make sure you were praying and then left?

15
00:00:52,708 --> 00:00:54,333
Yes, one of them
stood at the door

16
00:00:55,083 --> 00:00:57,833
Everyone performed <i>wudu</i>
[ablution] and the prayer was collective

17
00:00:59,041 --> 00:01:01,541
They prayed and finished,
then each returned to his place

18
00:01:09,166 --> 00:01:12,958
Interviewer: What sounds did you
hear from inside the detention room?

19
00:01:13,291 --> 00:01:16,041
And how was the smell
of the three rooms?

20
00:01:17,291 --> 00:01:19,541
I mean, the smell wasn’t good

21
00:01:19,541 --> 00:01:22,083
And we heard the voices
of those they were flogging

22
00:01:22,125 --> 00:01:27,333
And the crying of those
children I talked about

23
00:01:27,375 --> 00:01:29,750
Whose mothers were
here and being flogged

24
00:01:32,125 --> 00:01:34,083
I mean, I heard many things

25
00:01:34,416 --> 00:01:35,541
And sounds

26
00:01:41,541 --> 00:01:44,083
Interviewer: Was
the talk between you

27
00:01:44,125 --> 00:01:47,666
Or talk in general, was it
forbidden inside the cell?

28
00:01:47,666 --> 00:01:49,541
Between you and
the prisoners with you?

29
00:01:50,166 --> 00:01:51,500
No, no, it wasn't forbidden

30
00:01:52,208 --> 00:01:54,291
We would talk and chat

31
00:01:55,041 --> 00:01:58,791
But only a little

32
00:01:59,625 --> 00:02:01,708
We couldn't talk
about other things

33
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:04,375
Only about prayer matters

34
00:02:06,583 --> 00:02:10,125
Anyone who wanted to
learn the prayer and its details

35
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,458
Interviewer: Until what
hour did you talk together

36
00:02:16,500 --> 00:02:19,416
Did they come tell
you to stop and sleep?

37
00:02:19,458 --> 00:02:21,708
Or was it okay to
talk at other times?

38
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:26,000
At night after the prayer

39
00:02:26,458 --> 00:02:28,375
We chatted, then the
jailer came and yelled

40
00:02:28,416 --> 00:02:30,875
Enough, it's time to sleep

41
00:02:30,916 --> 00:02:32,083
And everyone slept

42
00:02:32,125 --> 00:02:35,041
No one stayed
awake—lights off, all slept

43
00:02:36,041 --> 00:02:41,375
If they heard anyone
talking or making a sound

44
00:02:41,666 --> 00:02:42,625
They would come up immediately

45
00:02:43,875 --> 00:02:46,666
They knocked—Who was
shouting? Who spoke?

46
00:02:48,083 --> 00:02:49,791
They checked,
then went back down
